"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 11–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-11-12.py

Historical/cultural/geographical context focus only.
NOT Greek lexical analysis (mkt-original) and NOT typology/Christology (mkt-christ).

Key context decisions for this range:
- Ch11 prison: Herod Antipas's fortress at Machaerus, east of the Dead Sea (Josephus, Ant. 18.119)
- John as Elijah: Mal 4:5 Second Temple expectation of Elijah's return before the Day of the Lord
- Marketplace children: familiar street game pattern; social metaphor for fickle reception
- Sabbath grain controversy (12:1-8): Deut 23:25 allowed hand-picking; Pharisaic halakha
  on Sabbath labor (m. Shabbat 7:2 lists 39 avot melachah, reaping is one)
- Beelzebul controversy: Jewish exorcism was widely practiced (Josephus, Ant. 8.2.5)
- Sign of Jonah: Jonah's three days in the fish as near-death/resurrection pattern
- v12:1 and v11:2 already covered; merge_comm skips them
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: Historical/cultural/geographical context for Matthew 11-12; covers Galilean
#   ministry response, Sabbath controversies, and Beelzebul debate.
# CHANGE? If verse keys change in data/interlinear/matthew.json, update dict keys here.
# VERIFY: Run script; confirm ch11 = 30 verses, ch12 = 50 verses in output.

MATTHEW = {
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>The transitional formula "when Jesus had finished instructing his twelve disciples" closes the Mission Discourse (ch. 10) and marks the resumption of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 own itinerant activity. The phrase "their cities" (<em>tais poleis autōn</em>) distinguishes Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 direct Galilean ministry from the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 parallel mission. Galilee\xe2\x80\x99s cities (Capernaum, Chorazin, Bethsaida, Nazareth) formed the primary geographic stage of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry in this period.</p>',
    "2": '<p>John the Baptist was imprisoned by Herod Antipas at Machaerus, a fortress-palace east of the Dead Sea in Peraea (Josephus, <em>Ant.</em> 18.5.2). Machaerus sat on a promontory overlooking the Jordan valley; it served as both administrative center and military stronghold. John\xe2\x80\x99s imprisonment followed his public rebuke of Antipas for marrying his brother Philip\xe2\x80\x99s wife Herodias (14:3-4) — a marriage that violated Levitical law (Lev 18:16; 20:21) and was politically scandalous. John received reports about Jesus from disciples allowed to visit him in custody.</p>',
    "3": '<p>John\xe2\x80\x99s question — "Are you the Coming One, or should we expect another?" — uses a recognized messianic title. "The Coming One" (<em>ho erchomenos</em>) draws on Ps 118:26 and Mal 3:1 ("the Lord whom you seek will suddenly come to his temple"). This was not a question about whether Jesus was a miracle-worker but whether he was the eschatological figure whose arrival would transform the present age. John\xe2\x80\x99s uncertainty from prison may reflect that the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s arrival did not look as he had preached: the ax was not yet laid to the tree (3:10).</p>',
    "4": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 instruction "go and report to John what you hear and see" places John in the tradition of the prophets who sought confirmation of their message (cf. 1 Kgs 19:9-18). The answer is not a direct "yes" but a catalogue of observable evidence — inviting John to perform the same hermeneutical work Jesus expected of the crowds: recognize what is happening by interpreting it against the prophetic grid.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The catalogue of healings deliberately echoes Isaiah\xe2\x80\x99s descriptions of the messianic age (Isa 29:18-19; 35:5-6; 61:1). Blind see, lame walk, lepers cleansed, deaf hear, dead raised, poor receive good news — each item corresponds to a specific Isaianic text. The cumulative list argues that what Isaiah promised as eschatological is happening in the present. The poor receiving good news (Isa 61:1) is particularly significant: the Gospel to the economically marginalized was a marker of the Jubilee age.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Blessed is the one who is not offended (<em>skandalisthē</em>) by me" addresses the specific stumbling block of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry style. Jesus was not the militant nationalist deliverer the popular imagination expected; he healed and taught rather than fought and ruled. The verb <em>skandalizō</em> (to cause to stumble) was used in Jewish literature for anything that caused apostasy or abandonment of covenant commitments. John and others had to recalibrate their messianic expectation against the evidence.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The rhetorical questions — "what did you go out to see?" (three times) — recreate the mass exodus to the Jordan that characterized John\xe2\x80\x99s early ministry (3:5-6). The wilderness (<em>erēmos</em>) carried powerful resonance: the Exodus generation was formed in the wilderness; the prophets had promised a new Exodus via the wilderness (Isa 40:3; Hos 2:14-15). People who went to the Judean wilderness were already expecting something eschatologically significant.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The contrast between the reed shaken by the wind and the man in soft clothing (<em>malakois himatiois</em>) distinguishes John from the royal court. Soft clothing belonged to palace luxury — Herod Antipas\xe2\x80\x99s court at Tiberias and Machaerus was known for its opulence. John\xe2\x80\x99s distinctive clothing (camel hair and leather belt, 3:4) deliberately evoked Elijah (2 Kgs 1:8) and identified him with the ascetic prophetic tradition rather than the comfortable establishment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>John is more than a prophet because he stands at the hinge of the ages rather than anticipating from a distance. In Second Temple Judaism, prophecy was widely believed to have ceased after Malachi; the restoration of prophetic voice in John was itself an eschatological sign that the long silence was breaking. John\xe2\x80\x99s position — at the threshold between the age of promise and the age of fulfillment — exceeded any previous prophetic role.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The citation of Mal 3:1 identifies John as the figure whose function was to prepare the way for the Lord\xe2\x80\x99s coming. In Malachi\xe2\x80\x99s context, the messenger preceded YHWH himself coming to his temple in judgment. The NT application places Jesus in the position of the coming Lord, making the identification theologically significant. Malachi 4:5 also promised the return of Elijah before "the great and terrible day of the Lord" — a tradition explicitly connected to John in v. 14.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Among those born of women no one has arisen greater than John the Baptist" employs a Semitic idiom ("born of women") for ordinary human beings (cf. Job 14:1). John\xe2\x80\x99s greatness consisted in his unique historical position: the last in the prophetic line, standing on the threshold of the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s arrival. Yet the least in the kingdom of heaven is greater — a comparative statement about eras, not personal merit: kingdom-participation exceeds prophetic anticipation.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"From the days of John the Baptist until now the kingdom of heaven has been subjected to violence" is one of Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s most debated verses. The <em>biastai</em> (violent men) who seize it by force can be read positively (earnest seekers pressing in) or negatively (opposition forces suppressing the kingdom). Given that John is imprisoned and Jesus is opposed by Pharisees and royal authorities, the negative reading fits: from John\xe2\x80\x99s arrest onward, the kingdom has faced aggressive opposition from those attempting to forcibly halt its advance.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"For all the prophets and the law prophesied until John" inverts the normal order (law before prophets). The combined "prophets and law" as a prophetic corpus points forward to the eschatological age; John stands at the end of that forward-pointing era. With John, the age of prophetic anticipation ends; with Jesus, the age of fulfillment begins. The law itself contained prophetic promise (the Pentateuch includes Balaam\xe2\x80\x99s oracles and Moses\xe2\x80\x99 Deuteronomic prophecies).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"If you are willing to accept it, he is Elijah who is to come" — the conditional frame acknowledges that this identification requires interpretive willingness. The Second Temple expectation of Elijah\xe2\x80\x99s literal return (Mal 4:5; Sir 48:10) was widespread: Elijah had not died but been taken up (2 Kgs 2:11), and his return was expected before the final judgment. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 identification of John as Elijah is typological rather than reincarnational — John comes "in the spirit and power of Elijah" (Luke 1:17), fulfilling the function Malachi described.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Let the one who has ears hear" marks teaching that requires interpretive engagement beyond surface hearing. The formula implies that the identification of John as Elijah was not obvious and would be resisted. Rabbinic tradition used similar formulas (<em>mi she-yesh lo oznayim</em>) to mark difficult or esoteric teaching. The audience is being invited to active discernment rather than passive reception.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The marketplace children (<em>paidaria en agorais</em>) provide the parable\xe2\x80\x99s social setting. The marketplace (<em>agora</em>) was the public open space at the center of a village or town — used for trade, civic assembly, and children\xe2\x80\x99s play. The specific game described — calling out for wedding dancing and funeral mourning — reflects the two primary social occasions requiring communal response. Children playing these games in the market square was an everyday village scene immediately recognizable to hearers.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Weddings required dancing; funerals required mourning. The children who refuse both are uncooperative with whatever is offered. The complaint is about the other children\xe2\x80\x99s refusal to engage with either mood — not about which game is correct. The social dynamic of peer pressure and group non-compliance was immediately recognizable to village audiences, and the parable\xe2\x80\x99s point was clear: some people will criticize any approach.</p>',
    "18": '<p>John came neither eating nor drinking — his ascetic practice (locusts and wild honey, 3:4; abstention from wine, Luke 1:15) was the correlate of the "dirge." The response was "he has a demon" — the social explanation for radical behavioral deviance that could not be explained by ordinary means. John\xe2\x80\x99s rigorous abstinence, outside the normal patterns of table fellowship, attracted this charge of supernatural malevolence.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Jesus came eating and drinking — table fellowship with tax collectors and sinners was the correlate of the "flute." The charge "a glutton and drunkard, a friend of tax collectors and sinners" invoked Deut 21:20\xe2\x80\x99s description of a rebellious son subject to stoning. The label was not merely moral criticism; it invoked a specific legal category. "Friend of tax collectors and sinners" attacked his social associations as incompatible with prophetic purity — and both charges, applied to Jesus and John, revealed the unfalsifiable double standard of the criticism.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The cities reproached — Chorazin, Bethsaida, and Capernaum — were precisely the cities where "his greatest miracles were done." The reproach is not for lack of exposure to evidence but for failure to respond to evidence abundantly received. Chorazin (modern Khirbet Kerazeh, 2-3 miles north of Capernaum) is not otherwise mentioned in the Gospel narratives, suggesting the written record preserved only a fraction of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 activity.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Tyre and Sidon were Phoenician coastal cities proverbially associated with wealth, trade, and Gentile luxury. In the prophetic tradition they were types of proud, doomed civilizations (Isa 23; Ezek 26-28; Amos 1:9-10). Sackcloth and ashes were the standard Jewish gestures of mourning and repentance: rough burlap replacing fine clothing, ashes on the head. The comparison argues that even these notorious Gentile cities would have responded more appropriately to the evidence that Chorazin and Bethsaida received.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The "day of judgment" (<em>hēmera kriseōs</em>) is the eschatological assize presupposed throughout apocalyptic Jewish literature: a final reckoning before the divine throne. The statement that Tyre and Sidon will fare better than Chorazin and Bethsaida introduces graduated judgment based on degree of revelation received — a principle that would be striking to any Jewish hearer who assumed Gentile cities stood under greater condemnation than Jewish ones.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Capernaum\xe2\x80\x99s address echoes the taunt against Babylon in Isa 14:13-15 ("You said in your heart, \'I will ascend to heaven\'... but you will be brought down to Sheol"). Capernaum was Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 adopted base and the site of more healing miracles than any other city; its failure to repent was correspondingly greater. The Sodom comparison was the most severe possible: Sodom\xe2\x80\x99s destruction was the OT archetype of total divine judgment with no restoration.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The comparison between Capernaum and Sodom uses the standard rabbinic form of judgment-day reasoning: relative guilt assigned on the basis of comparative information. Sodom sinned without having seen the works done in Capernaum; since Capernaum has seen the works and still rejected them, its culpability exceeds Sodom\xe2\x80\x99s. This graduated-judgment logic was familiar from Jewish apocalyptic literature and intertestamental texts.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The prayer of praise draws on the Wisdom tradition\xe2\x80\x99s theme of divine concealment and revelation. In Jewish Wisdom literature, God hides wisdom from the arrogant and reveals it to the humble (Job 28; Prov 1-9; Sir 1; 1 En. 42). The "wise and understanding" (<em>sophōn kai synetōn</em>) echoes Isa 29:14 ("the wisdom of their wise men shall perish"). The infants (<em>nēpiois</em>) are not the intellectually simple but the socially and spiritually humble who receive divine disclosure because they do not presume on their own status.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Yes, Father, for such was your gracious will" — the term <em>eudokia</em> (gracious will, good pleasure) is used in Jewish liturgical texts for God\xe2\x80\x99s sovereign delight and choice. The prayer\xe2\x80\x99s structure (thanksgiving for divine hiddenness from the wise) reflects a counter-intuitive theology of divine revelation common in Second Temple Jewish mystical texts: God\xe2\x80\x99s purposes operate through the unexpected and the lowly rather than through established power.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"All things have been delivered to me by my Father" — the claim of universal divine authority delegated to the Son is unprecedented in Jewish prophetic tradition. While Wisdom texts describe personified Wisdom sharing in divine creative and revelatory activity (Prov 8:22-31; Sir 24; Wis 7:25-26), a human figure claiming to be the exclusive mediator of divine knowledge of the Father is unique. The mutual-knowledge formula employs the intimate <em>da\'at</em> (knowing) relationship of the covenant between YHWH and Israel, now located in the Father-Son relationship.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The invitation draws on Wisdom\xe2\x80\x99s invitation in Sir 51:23-27: "Draw near to me, you who are uneducated, and lodge in my house of instruction... put your neck under her yoke." The "weary and burdened" had specific resonance: the Pharisaic interpretation of Torah had expanded commandments into 613 precepts plus extensive oral tradition. The burden of oral law observance on peasant workers who lacked access to scribal learning was real and heavy in first-century Galilee.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The yoke (<em>zygon</em>) was a standard metaphor for Torah submission. "Taking the yoke of the kingdom of heaven" (<em>qabbalat ol malkhut shamayim</em>) was a rabbinic phrase for accepting God\xe2\x80\x99s rule. Ben Sira\xe2\x80\x99s "yoke" was the yoke of Wisdom\xe2\x80\x99s instruction. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 "easy yoke" (<em>chrēstos</em> = kind, pleasant, manageable) contrasts not with Torah itself but with the interpretive tradition that had made Torah observance oppressive for ordinary people. "Gentle and lowly in heart" presents Jesus as the <em>anawim</em>-style leader who does not exploit his authority.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The promise "my yoke is easy and my burden is light" echoes Jer 6:16 ("ask for the ancient paths... and find rest for your souls") — a prophetic invitation that Israel had refused. The rest promised (<em>anapausin</em>) activates the Sabbath-rest theology that will immediately follow in the Sabbath controversies of ch. 12: true Sabbath rest is found in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 yoke, not in the burden of Pharisaic Sabbath-halakha.</p>'
  },
  "12": {
    "2": '<p>The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 complaint reflects a specific halakhic dispute. Deuteronomy 23:25 explicitly permitted hand-picking grain in a neighbor\xe2\x80\x99s field, so the issue was not gleaning but reaping-on-Sabbath. Pharisaic oral law classified thirty-nine categories of work forbidden on the Sabbath (<em>avot melachah</em>, Mishnah Shabbat 7:2); reaping was one of them. Hand-stripping grain heads was considered a form of reaping. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 action thus fell within the Pharisaic halakhic prohibition, even if it had no Torah proof-text.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 appeal to David\xe2\x80\x99s precedent (1 Sam 21:1-6) argues from a principle of human need overriding ritual restriction. David and his men ate the showbread reserved exclusively for priests (Lev 24:9) when they were hungry and fleeing Saul. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 point is not that rules don\xe2\x80\x99t matter but that they have a hierarchy: human welfare takes precedence over institutional regulations when the regulations were designed to serve human welfare. The appeal to David also carries an implicit messianic claim: what was legitimate for David in his need is legitimate for the Son of David.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The showbread (<em>tous artous tēs protheseōs</em>) consisted of twelve loaves placed before YHWH every Sabbath (Lev 24:5-9). After the new loaves replaced them, only priests could eat the old loaves within the sanctuary — explicit Torah, not merely oral tradition. Making Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 appeal to the Davidic precedent even more significant: he is appealing not to a lesser case but to a greater one. Even sacred priestly reserve was appropriately overridden by David\xe2\x80\x99s hunger.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The second precedent — priests performing Sabbath labor in the Temple — draws on Num 28:9-10 which commanded additional burnt offerings on the Sabbath. These offerings required the priests to work (slaughter animals, maintain fire, carry loads) in direct apparent violation of the Sabbath work prohibition. The halakhic resolution was that Temple service (<em>avodah</em>) overrode Sabbath restrictions. Jesus uses the same principle: if Temple service can override Sabbath, something greater than the Temple can also.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Something greater than the temple is here" — the Temple was the locus of God\xe2\x80\x99s presence in Israel, the center of the cosmos in Jewish theology, the place where heaven and earth met. To claim to be greater than the Temple was an extraordinary assertion. The claim links to 11:27\xe2\x80\x99s assertion that Jesus mediates knowledge of the Father exclusively; if the Temple\xe2\x80\x99s sanctity derived from God\xe2\x80\x99s presence, and Jesus embodies that presence, then his priority is theologically coherent.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The second Hosea 6:6 citation (the first at 9:13) reprises the prophetic critique of cultic formalism at the expense of covenant character. The application is precise: the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 Sabbath regulations had prioritized institutional correctness over human need and over the mercy that was the point of Sabbath rest. If they had understood what Hosea meant, they would not have condemned the guiltless — those whose actions were justified by the principle of human need that the Sabbath was designed to serve.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"The Son of Man is Lord of the Sabbath" — a direct claim to authority over the Sabbath institution. In Jewish theology, the Sabbath was not merely a law but a covenant sign marking Israel as YHWH\xe2\x80\x99s people (Exod 31:12-17; Ezek 20:12). To claim lordship over the Sabbath was to place oneself in the position of the Sabbath\xe2\x80\x99s giver — YHWH himself. The phrase "Son of Man" continues the Dan 7:13-14 resonance introduced at 9:6 (authority to forgive sins); here the authority extends to defining Sabbath observance itself.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Jesus moves from the grain field to the synagogue — from open countryside to the formal institutional setting of Jewish religious life. The synagogue was the primary community institution for Torah reading, prayer, legal interpretation, and communal assembly in Galilean villages. The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 presence there made it a site of formal legal debate rather than informal social encounter. The transition from Sabbath-grain controversy to Sabbath-healing controversy doubles down on the same halakhic question: what constitutes forbidden work on the Sabbath?</p>',
    "10": '<p>The question "Is it lawful to heal on the Sabbath?" was a genuine halakhic debate. The rabbinic answer was nuanced: life-threatening conditions permitted Sabbath medical intervention (<em>pikuah nefesh</em> — saving life overrides all commandments), but non-emergency conditions did not. A withered hand was not life-threatening; healing it on the Sabbath was therefore prohibited under Pharisaic interpretation. The question functions as a trap: if Jesus says "yes" he violates their halakha; if "no" he concedes their framework.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 counter-argument — "Which of you will have one sheep fall into a pit on the Sabbath and not take hold of it and lift it out?" — appeals to the universal practice of Sabbath rescue for endangered livestock. Some Qumran documents (CD 11:13-14) actually prohibited lifting an animal from a pit on the Sabbath, showing that even this was disputed in stricter communities. But Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 argument assumes the common-sense practice of all practical farmers against which the harder position would have seemed extreme.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"How much more is a person worth than a sheep!" employs the standard <em>qal wahomer</em> (lesser to greater) argument: if animal welfare justifies Sabbath labor, human welfare certainly does. The rhetorical question "so it is lawful to do good on the Sabbath" reframes the question from "what work is prohibited?" to "what is the purpose of Sabbath?" — a reframing that challenges the halakhic framework by locating the Sabbath\xe2\x80\x99s telos in human flourishing rather than in divine regulation alone.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The man with the withered hand likely had atrophy, nerve damage, or a developmental deformity. The social consequences were significant in a manual-labor economy: inability to work as a craftsman, farmer, or laborer. The healing was therefore economic and social restoration as much as physical. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 instruction "stretch out your hand" (which the man could not do before the healing) is the command that simultaneously demonstrates and constitutes the healing.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 council to destroy Jesus marks the first explicit death plot in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s narrative — a significant escalation from earlier debates. The council (<em>symboulion</em>) was a formal consultation; they "went out" from the synagogue to hold it, suggesting an official rather than informal decision. Mark 3:6 adds the Herodians as partners — a politically significant alliance between the religious establishment and the client-rulers of Galilee who had already imprisoned John.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 withdrawal (<em>anachōresen</em>) was strategic rather than fearful — timing management rather than cowardice. Throughout Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s Gospel, Jesus consistently withdraws from situations that would trigger premature confrontation with authorities before his appointed Passion (cf. 2:12, 14; 4:12; 14:13). The crowds following him and the healings continuing represent the uninterrupted mission despite official opposition.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The command not to make him known serves multiple pragmatic purposes: premature crowd enthusiasm could trigger Roman or Herodian intervention, Pharisaic opposition would increase, and a popular messianic movement based on healing power would distort the character of his mission. The Messianic secret in Matthew is less systematic than in Mark but serves a similar function: protecting the proper definition and timing of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 messianic identity against misappropriation.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The fulfillment formula introduces a direct citation of Isa 42:1-4 — the first Servant Song. The Servant Songs are four passages in Deutero-Isaiah (42:1-4; 49:1-6; 50:4-9; 52:13-53:12) describing the figure who accomplishes God\xe2\x80\x99s mission through suffering and service rather than military force. Matthew identifies Jesus with this Servant figure explicitly, grounding the withdrawal pattern and Messianic secret in a prophetic vision of a different kind of Messiahship.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Isaiah 42:1 — "Behold my servant whom I have chosen, my beloved in whom my soul is well pleased" — echoes the baptismal voice (3:17: "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased"). The verbal echo links the Servant Songs\xe2\x80\x99 Servant with the Son of the Baptism; Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 identity as "beloved Son" and as "Servant" are the same identity. The Spirit placed "upon" the Servant echoes the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s descent at the baptism (3:16).</p>',
    "19": '<p>"He will not quarrel or cry out, nor will anyone hear his voice in the streets" — the Servant\xe2\x80\x99s non-confrontational manner contrasts with the aggressive public style of street-preachers, political advocates, and popular Messianic claimants. In the first century, public disputation and loud proclamation in market squares characterized popular prophetic movements. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 withdrawal pattern and the charge to silence reflect exactly this non-public-display mode described by Isaiah.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"A bruised reed he will not break and a smoldering wick he will not quench" — the imagery describes the Servant\xe2\x80\x99s gentleness toward the fragile and failing. Reeds from the Jordan valley were used as measuring rods or musical instruments; a cracked reed was useless and would normally be discarded. A smoldering wick with nearly spent oil produced only smoke. The Servant\xe2\x80\x99s ministry is characterized by its care for those nearly destroyed or nearly extinguished — precisely the people Jesus has been healing throughout chs. 8-9.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"In his name the Gentiles will hope" — the climactic line of the Isaianic citation reaches beyond Israel to the nations. Isaiah 42:4 ends with the promise that the Servant\xe2\x80\x99s mission extends to the coastlands (Gentiles); Matthew cites this at a point where Jesus is primarily serving Galilean Jews, pointing forward to the Great Commission (28:19). The geographical and ethnic expansion of the mission is already written into Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 identity as the Servant of Isaiah.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The blind and mute demoniac represents compound afflictions that prevented both perception and communication. In the ancient world, such conditions were commonly attributed to demonic agency, as they affected multiple bodily systems simultaneously. The healing by exorcism both restored the man and demonstrated Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 power over demonic causation of illness — which immediately becomes the point of controversy in the Beelzebul debate.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The crowd\xe2\x80\x99s question — "Can this be the Son of David?" — is framed with a particle (<em>mēti</em>) expecting a tentative or negative answer: "This isn\xe2\x80\x99t the Son of David, is it?" The crowd is genuinely uncertain. The title "Son of David" carried specific military-messianic expectations from 2 Sam 7 and Ps 89 that Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 healing ministry was not obviously fulfilling. The astonishment was genuine but the identification was provisional and exploratory.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 formal response — "This man casts out demons only by Beelzebul, the ruler of demons" — was the institutional counter-narrative to crowd enthusiasm. Beelzebul (derived from the Philistine Baal-Zebub, 2 Kgs 1:2-3) had become a name for the chief demon in Second Temple demonology. The charge does not deny the reality of the exorcism but attributes it to demonic power rather than divine — neutralizing the miracle as evidence for Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 divine commissioning.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 counter-argument begins with the logical impossibility of a kingdom divided against itself. The political imagery — kingdom, city, house — was immediately comprehensible to people who had experienced the factional civil wars of the Hasmonean period and the threat of Herodian family division. A kingdom that fights itself is self-destructing; if Satan is expelling Satan, the demonic realm is engaged in self-defeating civil war.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"If Satan casts out Satan, he is divided against himself; how then will his kingdom stand?" exposes the incoherence of the Beelzebul charge by granting its premise for the sake of argument. If the exorcisms are Satan\xe2\x80\x99s work, then Satan is destroying his own power base — which makes no strategic sense for a kingdom seeking to maintain authority. The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 charge inadvertently implies that the demonic realm is in internal collapse.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"And if I cast out demons by Beelzebul, by whom do your sons cast them out?" — Jewish exorcism was widely practiced. Josephus describes Eleazar performing exorcisms before Vespasian using Solomonic techniques (Ant. 8.2.5); the Dead Sea Scrolls include exorcism texts (4Q196); Acts 19:13-14 refers to itinerant Jewish exorcists. If Jewish exorcists were legitimate, the charge of demonic power for exorcism would implicate the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 own students. Jesus turns the logical weapon on its users.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"But if it is by the Spirit of God that I cast out demons, then the kingdom of God has come upon you" (<em>eph\xe2\x80\x99 hymas</em> = upon you, in your present situation). The arrival of the kingdom is not future but present — it has "come upon" the Pharisees as a present fact they are refusing to acknowledge. The Spirit of God as the power behind exorcism activates the Isa 42:1 citation (12:18: "I will put my Spirit upon him"); the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s presence in the exorcisms is evidence that the Servant\xe2\x80\x99s mission is underway.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The strong man\xe2\x80\x99s house parable uses a household robbery analogy that was straightforwardly comprehensible: a house with a strong guardian cannot be robbed without first neutralizing the guardian. The "strong man" (<em>ho ischyros</em>) represents the demonic power maintaining affliction; the exorcisms are the plunder; the binding is what has made the exorcisms possible. The logic implies that a prior binding of demonic power has already occurred — possibly the temptation narrative (4:1-11) where Jesus refused to be co-opted by Satan.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"Whoever is not with me is against me, and whoever does not gather with me scatters" frames the Beelzebul controversy as a binary: there is no neutral position regarding Jesus. The gathering/scattering imagery echoes the Shepherd motif of Ezek 34 and Zech 10:2 — good shepherds gather, bad shepherds scatter. Jesus is gathering the scattered people of God (cf. 9:36: sheep without a shepherd); those who actively oppose him are scatterers.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The teaching on blasphemy against the Holy Spirit arises directly from the Beelzebul controversy. "Every sin and blasphemy will be forgiven people, but the blasphemy against the Spirit will not be forgiven" — the contrast is between sins in general and the specific act of attributing the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s work to demonic agency. The Pharisees have just done exactly this: they have seen the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s action in the exorcisms and declared it the work of Beelzebul.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The specific contrast — speaking against the Son of Man can be forgiven, but speaking against the Holy Spirit cannot — contextually refers to a sustained orientation: the deliberate, informed attribution of the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s evident work to demonic agency, in the face of overwhelming evidence. This is not accidental ignorance but willful rejection of what one recognizes to be divine. The unforgivability describes a state that has hardened itself against the very means by which forgiveness comes — not a limitation on divine mercy but a description of settled spiritual self-sealing.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The fruit-tree analogy applies agricultural logic to character: a diseased tree produces diseased fruit, a healthy tree healthy fruit. In Palestinian horticulture, fruit quality was a reliable indicator of tree health. The logic is directed at the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 charge: if the exorcisms are good fruit (healings, liberation), the tree producing them must be good. To call the fruit bad (demonic) commits them to calling the tree bad — which requires explaining the evident goodness of the outcomes.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Brood of vipers" (<em>gennēmata echidnōn</em>) — the same address John used in 3:7. The term <em>echidna</em> (viper) was particularly venomous in ancient Mediterranean identification. "From the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks" draws on Prov 4:23\xe2\x80\x99s teaching that the heart is the wellspring of life. Jewish Wisdom tradition consistently connected speech with character: what one says reveals what one is, because speech draws from the stored character-contents of the heart.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The "good treasure" and "evil treasure" of the heart develop the agricultural metaphor into a storage metaphor. In the ancient economy, wealth was stored in treasuries — physical locations where valuables were kept safe for later use. The heart is a character-treasury from which speech draws its content. Good character-formation produces a store of good; corrupt character-formation produces the opposite. Character is formed by the covenant commitments that shape one\xe2\x80\x99s interior life — Torah, prayer, practice.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"On the day of judgment people will give account for every careless word" — <em>rhēma argon</em> (careless/idle word) means words spoken without moral intention or accountability. The judgment-day accounting framework reflects Jewish apocalyptic recording theology: heavenly books record human deeds and words for eschatological review (Dan 7:10; 1 En. 89:61-64; Rev 20:12). Speech is cosmically registered, not private. The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 public attribution of the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s work to Beelzebul is exactly this kind of accountable speech.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"For by your words you will be justified and by your words you will be condemned" closes the Beelzebul pericope: the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 words attributing the Spirit\xe2\x80\x99s work to Beelzebul are exactly the kind of words that will serve as evidence at the judgment. Words are not separate from identity but are its expression; they carry the same covenantal weight as actions because they reveal and constitute character.</p>',
    "38": '<p>The scribes and Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 demand for a sign immediately after the Beelzebul controversy is remarkable: they have just witnessed exorcisms and healings. Signs (<em>ōtōt</em>) in the Jewish tradition meant publicly verifiable, institutionally recognized demonstrations of prophetic authentication — not private healings but spectacular, publicly undeniable interventions like Moses\xe2\x80\x99 plagues or Elijah\xe2\x80\x99s fire from heaven. They are asking for a credential in their preferred format rather than engaging with the evidence already before them.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign" — "adulterous generation" (<em>genea moichalis</em>) is prophetic language for covenant infidelity. In the OT prophets, Israel\xe2\x80\x99s unfaithfulness to YHWH was consistently described as adultery or prostitution (Hos 1-3; Jer 3:1-11; Ezek 16; 23). The generation that demands a sign while rejecting the evidence already given is playing the harlot — seeking spiritual satisfaction outside the covenant relationship. "No sign will be given except the sign of Jonah" names a single sufficient and fitting response.</p>',
    "40": '<p>"Just as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of the great fish" — Jonah\xe2\x80\x99s three-day entombment (Jon 1:17) was not a pleasant survival story but a near-death experience: Jonah\xe2\x80\x99s prayer from inside the fish (Jon 2) describes descent into Sheol and return. The "heart of the earth" (<em>tē̄ kardia̧ tēs gēs</em>) maps Jonah\xe2\x80\x99s fish-belly onto the realm of the dead. The Resurrection is the sign that could not be fabricated or demanded — it would be given at the appointed time.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The Ninevites\xe2\x80\x99 repentance at Jonah\xe2\x80\x99s preaching uses Nineveh — the Assyrian capital, the great enemy of Israel — as a model of appropriate reception of prophetic proclamation. Its citizens were considered by Jewish audiences the least likely candidates for genuine repentance. Yet they repented immediately on hearing Jonah\xe2\x80\x99s message, without witnesses to miracles. The comparison condemns the current generation who have had more evidence and a greater messenger and still refuse to respond.</p>',
    "42": '<p>The Queen of Sheba (1 Kgs 10:1-13; 2 Chr 9:1-12) came from the ends of the earth (Yemen or Ethiopia) to hear Solomon\xe2\x80\x99s wisdom — thousands of miles of travel demonstrating enormous commitment. Her condemnation of "this generation" follows the lesser-to-greater logic: she came from a great distance to hear Solomon\xe2\x80\x99s wisdom; the current generation has something greater than Solomon present and refuses to hear. Nineveh (Gentile penitents) and Sheba (Gentile wisdom-seeker) condemn the current generation from two angles.</p>',
    "43": '<p>The return of the unclean spirit uses the metaphor of a house for a person\xe2\x80\x99s inner life. When a demon leaves, it wanders through "waterless places" (<em>anydrous topous</em>) — arid desert regions understood in Jewish cosmology as the dwelling place of demons (cf. Isa 13:21; 34:14; Lev 16:10). The demon\xe2\x80\x99s wandering without rest reflects its need for a host body; it could not find rest in the waterless waste.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"I will return to my house from which I came out" — the demon\xe2\x80\x99s return to find the house swept and put in order (<em>scholazonta sesarōmenon kai kekosmēmenon</em>) describes religious reform without positive filling. In Jewish Wisdom literature, the good life required not just removing evil but replacing it with Torah study, prayer, and covenant practice. A "swept and empty" house represents external reform without inner transformation — the state of external compliance without covenant relationship.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"Then it goes and brings with it seven other spirits more evil than itself" — seven represented completeness of demonic occupation in Jewish demonological thinking; Mary Magdalene had been freed from seven demons (Luke 8:2). "The last state of that person is worse than the first" provides the interpretive application: the parable is directed at "this evil generation." Reform without allegiance to Jesus is unstable; the exorcisms Jesus has been performing need to be followed by discipleship, not left in a vacuum of clean-but-empty lives.</p>',
    "46": '<p>The arrival of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 mother and brothers while he is teaching creates a social interruption scene. In Mediterranean honor culture, family claims had priority over all other social obligations; an interruption from one\xe2\x80\x99s mother was not trivially overridden. The specific note that they "stood outside" implies they could not enter the crowded room. Mark 3:21 notes that the family had gone to "seize" Jesus because they thought he was out of his mind — providing context for why Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 response redefines the family relationship so radically.</p>',
    "47": '<p>"Your mother and your brothers are standing outside, seeking to speak to you" — the message was an appeal to normal family-priority social obligation. The expectation was that Jesus would suspend teaching and attend to his mother — the highest social obligation in a culture where filial piety was foundational. Matthew includes this verse to set up the redefinition of family that follows; the social pressure of the family claim makes Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 response all the more striking.</p>',
    "48": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 counter-question — "Who is my mother and who are my brothers?" — is a rhetorical device that reframes rather than answers literally. By turning the question back on the crowd, Jesus opens the definition of family beyond biological kinship. In Jewish and Greco-Roman culture, the household (<em>oikos</em>) was the fundamental social unit; to redefine family membership was to challenge one of the most foundational social institutions of the ancient world.</p>',
    "49": '<p>The gesture of stretching out his hand toward his disciples is a physical indicator of the redefined family. The disciples are his household — those who share his mission and submit to his teaching. This gesture would have been visible to both the crowd inside and the family outside, making the public statement unavoidable: the teaching community constitutes the primary family.</p>',
    "50": '<p>"For whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother" — the criterion for the new family is not biological descent but covenant obedience. This replicates OT covenant identity (Israel was God\xe2\x80\x99s family by covenant, not merely by nature) while relocating covenant membership in relation to Jesus. "My Father in heaven" is the characteristic Matthean address that distinguished Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 relationship to God from the general Jewish address "Our Father in heaven" (<em>avinu shebashamayim</em>) — Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 Father-relationship is one of unique intimacy (cf. 11:27).</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew')
    merge_comm(existing, MATTHEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew', existing)
    print('Matthew 11-12 mkt-context written.')
    for ch in ['11', '12']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
